<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=F000195. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->'''Anthony Alfred Fleger''' ([[October 21]], [[1900]] - [[July 16]], [[1963]]) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Ohio]].

Born in Austria-Hungary, Fleger<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->In 1903 immigrated to the United States with his parents, who settled in [[Cleveland, Ohio]].
He attended the public schools and was graduated from John Marshall School of Law, [[Cleveland, Ohio]], in 1926.
He was admitted to the bar the same year and commenced practice in [[Cleveland, Ohio]].
He moved to [[Parma, Ohio]], and continued the practice of law.
He served as [[Justice of the Peace]] in [[Parma, Ohio]] from 1930 to 1932.

Fleger was elected a member of the State house of representatives in 1932 and served from [[January 1]], [[1933]], to [[December 31]], [[1933]], when he resigned, having been elected mayor of Parma.
He served as mayor from [[January 1]], [[1934]], to [[December 31]], [[1935]].

Fleger was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the Seventy-fifth Congress ([[January 3]], [[1937]]-[[January 3]], [[1939]]).
He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1938 to the Seventy-sixth Congress and for election in 1940 to the Seventy-seventh Congress.
He resumed the practice of law in [[Cleveland, Ohio]].
He served as special assistant to the Attorney General, [[Washington, D.C.]], from [[March 3]], [[1941]], to [[July 9]], [[1950]], and as an attorney in the Department of Justice from [[July 10]], [[1950]], to [[May 9]], [[1953]].
He engaged in the practice of law in [[Washington, D.C.]], and resided in [[Oxon Hill, Maryland]].
He died in Alexandria (Virginia) Hospital [[July 16]], [[1963]].
He was interred in Holy Cross Cemetery, [[Brook Park, Ohio]].

